The paper deals with distributed hypothesis testing in multi-agent networks, which involves information exchange and collaboration among agents. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) or Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-categories. The paper also considers the impact of failures and asynchrony, which are fundamental factors in distributed systems, indicating that it may also belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The use of non-Bayesian learning and consensus-based methods suggests that the paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with networked agents and submatrices, which suggests that it may also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category.
